{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17600769","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17600769"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T12:07:28+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T12:07:28+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15630"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15630","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15630"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.13,0.29,0.46,0.08,0.04]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8321"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"70484"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8321","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8321"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15630"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"55948"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4929"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"4949"},{"type":"tags","id":"7010"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"20077"},{"type":"contributions","id":"20080"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"70484","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/70484"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EDuring embryological development, the adrenal gland forms from two distinct tissue origins.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following describes the embryological origin of the adrenal cortex?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Endoderm","Neural crest cells","Mesoderm","Surface ectoderm","Ectoderm"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe adrenal gland develops from two distinct embryological origins. The \u003Cstrong\u003Emesoderm\u003C/strong\u003E gives rise to the adrenal cortex, specifically the intermediate mesoderm and coelomic epithelium. This forms the steroid-producing outer portion of the gland.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe other options are incorrect: \u003Cstrong\u003Eendoderm\u003C/strong\u003E forms the gastrointestinal tract and associated organs; \u003Cstrong\u003Eectoderm\u003C/strong\u003E forms the epidermis and nervous system; \u003Cstrong\u003Eneural crest cells\u003C/strong\u003E (which are derived from neuroectoderm) form the adrenal medulla; and \u003Cstrong\u003Esurface ectoderm\u003C/strong\u003E forms the epidermis, eyes, mouth, nasal cavity, teeth and several glands.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThis dual embryological origin explains the distinct functions of the adrenal cortex (steroid hormone production) and medulla (catecholamine production).\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The adrenal cortex develops from mesoderm, specifically intermediate mesoderm and coelomic epithelium.","The adrenal medulla develops separately from neural crest cells (neuroectoderm)."],"references":["Melmed, S., Polonsky, K. S., Larsen, P. R., \u0026 Kronenberg, H. M. (2015). Williams textbook of endocrinology E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Clark, O. H., Duh, Q. Y., Kebebew, E., Gosnell, J. E., \u0026 Shen, W. T. (Eds.). (2016). Textbook of endocrine surgery. JP Medical Ltd","Young, W. F. (2011). Netter\u0027s Endocrine System: Netter Collection of Medical Illustrations: Endocrine System E-book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Wass, J. A., \u0026 Stewart, P. M. (Eds.). (2011). Oxford textbook of endocrinology and diabetes. Oxford University Press, USA.","Torchia, M. G., \u0026 Persaud, T. V. N. (2020). Concise Clinical Embryology: an Integrated, Case-Based Approach. Elsevier Health Sciences"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions",